{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17660236","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17660236"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:21:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:21:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22758"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22758","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22758"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15705"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111981"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15705","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15705"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22758"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94045"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"45698"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45858"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111981","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111981"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe stomach has a rich blood supply, with various vessels supplying its different areas. The photograph shows a stomach that has just been resected. The arrow points to one area of the stomach (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"To which of the following blood vessel(s) does the arrow point?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Short gastric vessels","Left gastro-epiploic arcade","Right gastro-epiploic arcade","Right gastric artery","Left gastric artery"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe resected specimen shows all of the stomach from the cardia down to the pylorus. The spleen is attached. The regions of the stomach and their blood supply are shown (Image):\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFundus - short gastric vessels (arrow B)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBody - left gastric and left gastro-epiploic vessels (arrow C)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGreater curvature - right and left gastro-epiploic vessels (arrows C and E)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPylorus - right gastric and right -gastro-epiploic vessels (arrows E and H)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELesser curvature - right and left gastric arteries (arrow H)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn the photograph the arrow (C) is pointing towards the proximal part of the greater curve of the stomach - which is fed by the \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft gastro-epiploic arcade\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The blood supply of the stomach comes from branches of the coeliac trunk, namely, the left gastric, splenic and common hepatic arteries."],"references":["Soybel DI. Anatomy and Physiology of the Stomach. Surg Clin North Am. 2005; 85:875-94. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16139026/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94045"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22758"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"22061"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"22065"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"22061","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/22061"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/0yBA4kvXCNytVwoDlk543tOAQ9hSLm.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/0yBA4kvXCNytVwoDlk543tOAQ9hSLm.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":330,"heigh